@REMARK ----------------------------------------------------------------

@NODE AboutHelp "About this help guide       [V3.102 (17.10.94)]"

This is the Commodore Helping System AmigaGuide (R).
To get more information about it, click the HELP gadget above or
press the H key.

When running the M&M Editor you can call this guide in two ways:

  1. by pressing the HELP key.
  2. by selecting a menu item while pressing the HELP key. You will get
     specific information about the selected menu item.

You also can call an @{" Index " link myIndex}.

@ENDNODE

@REMARK ----------------------------------------------------------------

@NODE Installation "Installation of Menus & More"

You can easily install M&M by executing the M&M project

   First!.M&M

It's in the M&M drawer and can be started by double-clicking.
After the menu screen appears, select "Installation" or press F2.


Please notice that the "MMEditor" program is calling the following files:

    - "M&M.config"	the configuration file.
    - "M&M.icon"	the default project-icon used by MMEditor.
    			Change it, if you want...
    - "M&M.guide"	The AmigaGuide file - the text you are reading
    			just now...

All these files should be in the same drawer as all M&M programs!


All projects in the "Examples" drawer are calling the directory

   "MM:Beispiele"

It should be assigned in the user-startup file in the S: directory:

   Assign MM: DH0:Tools/M&M      (for example)


The following libraries are used:

  asl.library		Version 36+
  AmigaGuide.library	Version 34+
  diskfont.library	Version 33+
  rexxsyslib.library	Version 36+

They should be in the LIBS: directory.

Some example projects are calling the original Commodore "ED"
from Workbench 2.x and higher. It should be in the C: directory.


@{"Complete overview of all files" link FileList

@ENDNODE

@REMARK ----------------------------------------------------------------

@NODE FileList "List Of Important Files"

The following files should be in the M&M directory:


MMEditor		The Menus & More editor program.

MMPlayer		The Menus & More player progrmm.

MMReq			A tool for usage in dos-scripts.

MMAnalyse		A tool for writing the names of all
			screens used by a M&M project.

M&M.config		The MMEditor's configuration file.

M&M.icon		The default icon used by MMEditor.

M&M.guide		The AmigaGuide file - this text.

ReadMe.guide		A short introduction guide.

First!.M&M		Introductionary & Installation.

Deutsch			German catalog files

Examples (drawer)	Example menu projects.


@ENDNODE

@REMARK ----------------------------------------------------------------

@NODE AboutMM "About Menus & More"

What can I do with Menus & More?

   With Menus & More (M&M) you are able to create graphic orientated
   screen menus. Once you have installed your own menu, you can easily
   call many programs from one central screen. It's just like designing
   your own graphical user interface without doing any programming.
   All you have to know is how to start your programs from CLI.

   Because of the great amount of options, you are able to produce
   even more than just menus - as the name of program indicates!


How are these menus constructed?

  The basic of all menu projects are screens. These screens are
  nothing else than simple IFF pictures, which can be painted
  easily with programs like DPaint (TM) or similar.
  The screen contains the menu as a picture: Every option to be
  selected has to be drawed as a button. Now you have to tell M&M
  the name of the screen, where the buttons are and finally what
  should be happen, if the menu's user clicks on a button.


Based upon a screen, you can make use of the following elements
within a menu project:

  buttons	the (painted) buttons mentioned above.
  		After selection, a command given by the creator
  		of the menu will be executed.

  menus		the original Amiga Intuition pull-down menus.
  		A command is executed after selection, too.

  displays	a status text on the screen. You can display
  		the time, date or the free amount of ram.

When creating and editing a menu with MMEditor, every element
(screen, button, pull down menu and display) has its own window.
Cnf. @{"the MMEditor's window" link Windows}.


Overview:

			S C R E E N S
		       /      |      \
		   buttons  menus  displays
		      |       |
		   command command


How can I create such a menu project?

  You have to use the @{"MMEditor" link MMEditor} program for this purpose.
  Created menus will be stored as menu project on disk. This project file
  contains all information necessary to build the menus. For example
  the filenames of the iff pictures used in the project, which commands
  shall be executed and so on.


How can I run the menu?

  The menus are executed with the @{"MMPlayer" link MMPlayer} program.
  It loads all necessary files and "plays" the menu.


Another overview about the creating and running of a menu project:


			 ------------
      IFF pictures ----> | MMEditor | -----> creates ------
      (=screens)         ------------                    ||
	  |    						 ||
	  |    						 \/
	  |    					  ----------------
	  |    					  | menu-project |
	  |    					  ----------------
	  |    					          |
	  |    					          |
	  |    		 ------------		          |
	  --- loads --> | MMPlayer  | <------ loads -------
	      		 ------------
                              ||
                            plays
                              ||
                              ||
                              \/
                             user

@ENDNODE

@REMARK ----------------------------------------------------------------

@NODE MMEditor "MMEditor - the Menus & More Editor"

With the help of the MMEditor program, you are able to create
good looking graphical menus.

Start from Workbencch:

  - by double-clicking the MMEditor icon.

  - by clicking on a menu project icon, holding the shift-key
    and double clicking the MMEditor icon. The given menu project
    will be opened automatically.

  Note: you can edit the @{"MMEditor's tooltypes" link EdToolTypes} when working
        with the Workbench.


Start from CLI:

  - by typing	1> Stack 8192
  		1> MMEditor


After the MMEditor has been started, the @{"MMEditor's screen" link EdScreen} will be opened.

@ENDNODE

@REMARK ----------------------------------------------------------------

@NODE Locale "Locale.library"

Normally, the language used within MMEditor is english. But
you can use other labguages. Currently, only @{"german" link LocaleD} is available.

So, if you want to create a catalog for another language,
please @{"contact me" link Axel}! As a donation, you will get
a free registration...

@ENDNODE

@REMARK ----------------------------------------------------------------

@NODE EdToolTypes "ToolTypes of MMEditor"

You can change the following tooltypes within the icon's "Information"-
requester:


  WINDOW=doswin

    "doswin" has to be a legal desciption of a AmigaDos window.
    The outputs of the @{"start commands" link StartComm} will be printed into this
    window.

    Preset: CON:0/0/400/200/M&M/AUTO/CLOSE/WAIT


  SCRWINHEIGHT=pixel

    You can change the height of @{"screens window" link ScrWin} with this tooltype.
    "pixel" has to be greater than 80.

    Preset: 100


  WINHEIGHT=pixel

    This tooltypes indicates the height of all @{"other windows" link Windows} (buttons,
    menus and displays). "pixel" has to be greater than 160.
    When pixel is set to -1, the windows will fit perfectly below the
    screens window.

    Preset: -1


  FILEBUFFER=bytes

    A bigger filenbuffer uses more memory but speeds up the disk
    operation (load/save).

    Preset = 1024


  ERRORREPORT=ON/OFF

    If an error occurs within a test run, a complete error message
    will appear, if this tooltype is set to ON.

    Preset: ON


  PICPATTERN=dospat

    The file requester which appears when a new IFF picture
    is opened, uses an AmigaDos pattern to match out all
    non IFF files. When the preset remains unchanged, only
    files with the suffix ".pic" will be displayed in the file
    requester.

    Preset: #?.pic


  SHELLSTART=comseq

    This command string will be executed after the menu item
    @{"Extras/Shell" link LaunchShell} has been selected in the MMEditor.

    Preset: NewShell "CON:0/0/400/200/CLOSE/MMShell/SCREENMMEditor


  SHELLSTACK=bytes

    If your favourite shell needs a bigger stack, tell it MMEditor
    by this toolype.

    Preset: 4096


  EDSTART=comseq

    This command string will be executed after the menu item
    @{"Extras/Editor" link LaunchEd} has been selected in the MMEditor.

    Preset: C:Ed FROM:CON:0/0/400/200/AUTO/CLOSE/Editor/SCREENMMEditor


  EDSTACK=bytes

     cnf. SHELLSTACK


  PAINTSTART=comseq

    This command string will be executed after the menu item
    @{"Extras/Painting" link LaunchPaint} has been selected in the MMEditor.

    Preset: DPaint:DPaint


  PAINTSTACK=bytes

    cnf. SHELLSTACK

@ENDNODE

@REMARK ----------------------------------------------------------------

@NODE EdScreen "MMEditor's work screen"

Regarding mode, resolution and colors, the screen opened by MMEditor
is a clone of the workbench screen. But there are (currently!) two
exceptions:

  - MMEditor always uses an eight pixel height topaz font.

  - MMEditor's screen always has a depth of 2 bit-planes.

Hopefully, these disadvantages will be banished in the next versions :-)


The screen is a public screen with the name 'MMEditor', if you started
it twice (why?!), the name is 'MMEditor.2' and so on.


There will be one @{"window" link Windows} opened on the screen for every element, which can
be used in a menu.

@ENDNODE

@REMARK ----------------------------------------------------------------

@NODE Windows "MMEditor's windows"

The screen of MMEditor is devided into different windows:

  @{" the 'Screens'  - window " link ScrWin}

  @{" the 'Buttons'  - window " link ButWin}
  @{" the 'Menus'    - window " link MenWin}
  @{" the 'Displays' - window " link DisWin}

The screens window is open at any case.

The three other windows will be opened, if

  - a screen is loaded by choosing 'New' or 'Insert' in the screens window.

  - a project has been @{"opened" link Open}.

This is, because you can only create a button or install a pulldown menu
if you have already selected the basic iff picture, the screen.

The width of the windows will be the same as the width of @{"editor's screen" link EdScreen}.
However, their vertikal positions are freely adjustable. The settings can
be stored in the @{"configuration file" link SaveConfig}.

The height of the windows can be changed by using the @{"tooltypes" link EdToolTypes}.

When using the standard settings of the window's position, you can
make out the current screen at every time.

By using the function keys, the windows can easily be switched to the
front of the screen:

  - [F1] to bring the 'Screens' window to front.
  - [F2] "    "    "  'Buttons'    "   "    ".
  - [F3] "    "    "  'Menus'      "   "    ".
  - [F4] "    "    "  'Displays'   "   "    ".

You can also switch the button-, menu- or displays-window on or off
either by clicking the CLOSE gadget in the upper left corner of the
window or by selecting the menu item @{"Window On/Off" link SwitchWins}.

The scrolling of a listview can also be done by pressing the
cursor up- or down-key (jump to the start or end by shifting).

@ENDNODE

@REMARK ----------------------------------------------------------------

@NODE ScrWin "Screens-window"

You can manage all affairs concerning the menu's screens within
this window.

A listview of all screens used by the current menu will be displayed,
the actual screen will be highlighted. Like any listview in MMEditor,
you can choose the actual screen by using the cursor up or down keys.


With 'Add', you can add a new screen to the list.

With 'Insert' you can insert a screen before the actual screen.

With 'Clear' you can delete the actual screen from the list.


After clicking on 'Edit' you have the chance to set further parameters:

  - the @{"font" link ScrFont} used by the screen.
    After choosing a new font, the iff picture will be reloaded.
    This is currently the only way of linking the new font to the
    screen.

  - whether the title shall be displayed or not

  - a command BEFORE the screen is loaded.
    The AmigaDos command typed in this field will be executed,
    before the iff picture is displayed.

  - a command AFTER the screen is loaded.
    The AmigaDos command typed in this field will be executed,
    after the iff picture is displayed (huh?! shocking!)


After 'Info' is selected, a requester with some information
about the actual screen appears. If you plan to use another screen
(concerning resolution and depth) while all buttons, menus etc.
shall remain, you can 'select a new one'.


@{"More hints concerning screen" link ScreenHints}

@ENDNODE

@REMARK ----------------------------------------------------------------

@NODE StartComm "Startup commands"

M&M gives you the possibility of starting a dos command before a menu
screen ist loaded and one after loading. This can be very useful for
initialization purposes.

Example: It is a good idea to assign a directory to a logical device
in order to link all filenames to this device.

	command before loading:	Assign MyMenu: SYS:M&M/Data

	Examples for filenames used within the menu project:
	  MyMenu:FirstPicture.pic	(a menu screen)
	  MyMenu:Info.txt		(a textfile)

So it's easy to change the directory containing the necessary files
without changing the whole menu.

When assigning MyMenu: to "" (via Assign MyMenu: ""), MyMenu: will
always point to the current directory. I did so within the 'First!.M&M
project.

You are also able to run scripts via 'Execute script' as startup command.


Please notice the output of your startup commands:

   If you started the menu from workbench, you can select the
   output stream via the @{"WINDOW tooltype" link EdToolTypes} within
   MMEditor or MMPlayer:

   	WINDOW=CON:x/y/b/h/Name/Option		(cnf. your DOS manual!)


   If you started it from CLI, the CLI window will be the
   output stream.

@ENDNODE

@REMARK ----------------------------------------------------------------

@NODE ScrFont "Font used by a menu screen"

Every screen used within a menu can have it's own font. This font
is used

  - in the screen's title

  - the pulldown menu titles

  - the @{"displays" link DisWin}

@ENDNODE

@REMARK ----------------------------------------------------------------

@NODE ScreenHints "Some Information about the menu's screens"

The screens are nothing else than IFF pictures, which can easily be
created with programs like DPaint(TM) or similar. Every resolution
and depth can be used, AGA modes are supported.

The menu's project file contains information about the height, width,
number of planes and the display id. You can look at these values by
selecting 'Info' within the screens window. Because of the storing
of these values, it is not possible to change any of these values
(by adding a plane or using a bigger resolution for example) after
the screen is already part of the menu. If done so, M&M can't
open the screen correctly.
So, for changing a screen, you HAVE to use the 'select a new one'
function within the info requester.

Another problem is the use of masking data. Please switch every
mask off before you save you menu picture to disk!

@ENDNODE

@REMARK ----------------------------------------------------------------

@NODE ButWin "Buttons-window"

This window will only open, if a menu screen has been loaded.

The name of the actual button is displayed below a listview gadget
which contains a list with the names of all used buttons.

'Add'		a new button at the end of the list. After selection,
		you have to @{"set the button's area" link GetButton}.

'Insert'	a new button before the actual button in the list.
		You have to set the button's area, too.

'Clear'		deletes the actual button from the list.

'Edit'		let's you reset the button's area.


You have to tell MMEditor, which @{"command" link Commands} should be done
after selectingthe current button and whether there should be a @{"parameter request" link Asks}
before executing or not.

'Select'	the argument passed to the action.
		This can be a file like an AmigaDos command or
		an ARexx programm or the name of a screen, a
		AmigaDos return value...

'Option'	you can set more options concerning the selected command.
		Some commands like 'Quit Menu' don't have any options, so
		the gadget will be ghosted.

'Key'		the button can be selected either by clicking or by
		pressing a corresponding key. Type the key, which
		represents the current button, into this field. If
		you want to use a special key, select the 'Key' gadget.

@{"Click here to get more hints about buttons!" link ButtonHints}

@ENDNODE

@REMARK ----------------------------------------------------------------

@NODE GetButton "Setting the button's area"

Setting the button's area is done in following way:

  1. The menu screen will be brought to front.
  2. Select the upper left corner of the button with
     the left mouse button.
  3. Hold left mouse button
     (if you want to select another corner, just press the esc key)
  4. go to the button's lower right corner.
  5. release mouse button.

It's not always an easy job to mark just the right area of the button.
To make is simplier, a function called 'Lasso' has been implemented.
You switch in on (and off) with the space bar. Once switched on, you
only have to mark the approximate area, the button will be searched
automatically. Just try it!

With the F10 key, you can the switch the screen's title while
setting the area of the button.

After the setting procedure, the button's name will be requested.
You cannot use a name twice within a list.

@ENDNODE

@REMARK ----------------------------------------------------------------

@NODE ButtonHints "Some clues concerning the menu's buttons"

There is a problem when you insert a new button in the list: The IDs
of the gadget are not re-calculated every time a new button is inserted.
So it is possible that a button will not be recognized while
test-running.

The problem can be solved in two ways:

  If you have only one screen: Save the project, select 'New Project' and
  open it again. A test-run will do fine now.

  If you have more than one screen, it is easier: just select another
  screen, then select the "fault one". Test-run will be working again.

@ENDNODE

@REMARK ----------------------------------------------------------------

@NODE MenWin "Menus-window"

This window contains a list of all intuition pulldown menu items
used within the M&M menu.

To create such a pulldown menu, select @{"'Edit'" link GetMenus}.

Single items can be 'Insert'ed or 'Clear'ed.

After editing the pulldown menu, you have to set @{"the request" link Asks} and
@{"the command" link Commands} linked to the different items - just like the way you
did it in the @{"buttons window link ButWin}.

@{"Click here to get some hints about menus!" link MenuHints}

@ENDNODE

@REMARK ----------------------------------------------------------------

@NODE GetMenus "Editing the pulldown menus"

The actual menu screen (your iff picture) will be zapped into the front.

Then a window is opened: Here you can edit your personal menu. All you
have to do is to type the title and the linked items. With 'Add' you
can add a new title to your menu or 'Insert' a new one.

You can set a menu selection key (right Amiga + X, for example) for
every item.

Jump with the enter key from one item to another, for jumping to
the selection key field use the TAB key (shifted to jump back).

With the cursor left and right key, you can jump from one title
to the next.

By selecting the 'Font' gadget, a new font concerning (only!) the
menu items can be choosen. The font of the menus titles is choosen
in the @{"screen edit window" link ScrWin}.

You are also able to 'Clear' one, all or none item(s).


Please notice:

  The maximum number of titles to be edited is currently 15.

  The maximum number of items is currently set to 15, too.
  BUT: if you use a menu screen with a very small height, the
  space for the editing window is limited - thus the number
  of editable items will be decreasing!

@ENDNODE

@REMARK ----------------------------------------------------------------

@NODE MenuHints "Some Hints concerning pulldown menus"

The highest number of editable menu title is 15.
Every title can have 15 items at maximum.

No more hints currently...   :-(

@ENDNODE

@REMARK ----------------------------------------------------------------

@NODE DisWin "Displays-window"

'Add'		adds a new status display to the list.

'Insert'	inserts a new display into the list.

'Clear'		clears an existing display.


Set up a new status display in the following way:

  Select 'Edit', a window will appear on the menu screen.
  Now you can change

  - the x- and y-position of the text,

  - one string appearing before the specific information to
    be displayed and one string after and

  - the display modus (free memory, time or date), which sets
    the specific information mentioned above.


Set the x- and y-position easily with the mouse by clicking
'New position'.


M&M will construct the status display in the following way:

  [string before] [ ] [display] [ ] [string after]

  Example:	before: "Time:"		  \
  		 after: "o'clock"	   > "Time: 16.24.13 o'clock"
  		  mode: "Time - 16.24.13" /

Please notice the space character between the different elements.

And notice too that you cannot change the display's color (it is
the complement of the color underlying the display - try it!).

The last worth noticing is the fact that the font of the display is
the @{"menu-screen's font" link ScrFont} (which you can set in the screen's edit window).


@ENDNODE

@REMARK ----------------------------------------------------------------

@NODE AllMenus "Menus of MMEditor"

The menu of MMEditor is devided into four parts:

1.Project         @{" New                   " link New}
                  @{" Open...               " link Open}
                  @{" Save                  " link Save}
                  @{" Save as...            " link Save}
                  @{" About...              " link About}
                  @{" Quit...               " link Quit}

2.Testrun         @{" from current screen   " link RunCurrScr}
                  @{" from first screen     " link RunFirstScr}
                  @{" Execute Commands...   " link PlayerModes}

3.Settings        @{" Buttons window?         " link SwitchWins}
                  @{" Menus window?           " link SwitchWins}
                  @{" Displays window?        " link SwitchWins}
                  @{" Create Icons?           " link CreateIcons}
                  @{" Save Settings           " link SaveConfig}

4. Extras         @{" Copy commands...     " link CopyCommands}
                  @{" Launch Shell         " link LaunchShell}
                  @{" Launch Editor        " link LaunchEditor}
                  @{" Launch Painting Tool " link LaunchPaint}
                  @{" Help                 " link AboutHelp}


@ENDNODE

@REMARK ----------------------------------------------------------------

@NODE New "Project New"

Select this item to clear the current menu project from memory.

If the project has not been saved before, a requester giving you
the chance to do that, appears.

@ENDNODE


@NODE Open "Open project"

To open an existing menu project from disk.
Choose it in the file requester.

The following errors are possible:

   - the selected file is not a M&M file.
   - the selected file has an incorrect format.
   - there is not enough free memory.

@ENDNODE


@NODE Save "Save project (as)"

To save a menu project to disk.

If you are saving a project the first time - the file name is 'NoName.M&M' -
the requester will appear.

If your project already has a filename, you can

	'Save'		with the same name

	'Save as'	a new project with a new filename.

@ENDNODE


@NODE About "About..."

You will get information about:

  - the version of MMEditor you are currently using
  - the author @{"Axel Sodtalbers" link Axel}
  - the copyright
  - the free amount of memory

Furhter, you can get information about

  -     User: the registration entry
  - Internal: name of the MMEditor's (!) public screen
  	      language used by MMEditor (built-in or deutsch)

  	      name of the MMPlayer's (!) public screen
  	      name of the Player's ARexx-Port (used within test run)

@ENDNODE


@NODE Quit "Quit..."

To quit MMEditor.

Do you really want to quit this fabulous program? (sniff!)  :-(

@ENDNODE

@REMARK ----------------------------------------------------------------

@NODE RunCurrScr "Testrun from current screen"

If you want to test the menu, select this item. The test will be
started at the actual menu screen.

Don't forget to implement a 'Quit' button or pulldown menu in your
menu by using the 'Quit menu' command! But you can stop the testrun
by pressing the ctrl- and the esc-key at any time.

@ENDNODE


@NODE RunFirstScr "Testrun from first screen"

This item has the same function as @{"testrun from current screen" link RunCurrScr}
except that the testrun will always start at the first screen in
the list.

Thus the selection will do the same than running the @{"MMPlayer" link MMPlayer} and is
a good opportunity to test your complete menu.

@ENDNODE


@NODE PlayerModes "Execute commands always/by request/never"

Here you can choose what shall happen if you select a button or
menu with a 'Execute dos command' or 'Switch to other screen' command
function while testrunning.

  - always		the dos command will be executed in any case.

  - by request		a request appears so that you can select
  			whether the command shall be runned or not.
  			This is recommended if your menu contains
  			"dangerous" functions like deleting files or
  			formating disks...

  - never		the dos command won't be executed.

The actual setting will be stored in the @{"configuration file" link SaveConfig}.

The @{"startup commands" link StartComm} (before and after loading the menu screen) are
concerned, too.

@ENDNODE

@REMARK ----------------------------------------------------------------

@NODE SwitchWins "Switching a window on or off"

You can close or open any window - execept the screen window by
clicking the close gadget in the upper left corner or by selecting
just this menu item.

The three windows (button, menu and display) will only open if there
is a menu screen in memory (cnf. @{"the window system" link Windows}).
Thus these menu items are only selectable when you have loaded a
screen.

The status of any window (opened or closed) can be stored in the
configuration file by selecting @{"save settings" link SaveConfig}.

@ENDNODE


@NODE CreateIcons "Create Icons?"

If you want a project icon stored to disk together with you menu,
select this item.

If it exists, the icon called "M&M.icon" in the M&M directory will
be used - otherwise the standard workbench icon.

@ENDNODE


@NODE SaveConfig "Save settings"

After selecting this item, the current configuration of MMEditor
will be stored in the 'M&M.config' file in the directory, MMEditor
has been started from. It contains:

  - the @{"window's" link Windows} vertical position, opened or not

  - the @{"mode of executing commands" link PlayerMode} within a testrun

  - the position and size of the file-requester

  - the position and size of the font-requester

  - whether MMEditor shall @{"produce an icon when saving a project" link Icons} or not

@ENDNODE

@REMARK ----------------------------------------------------------------

@NODE CopyCommands "Copy commands..."

It is very annoying to produce the same actions for many different
screens within one menu project. Too, it is no fun to create one
pulldown menu with the same function for every button.

Thus the possibility to copy commands between buttons, between menus
or between button and menus has been implemented.

After calling this function, a window containing to lists appears:
the left lists marks which function shall be copied,
the right one where to.

You can switch every list to a buttons or a menus list.

Use the cursor key alternatively to move whithin the lists:
up and down in the left list, left and right in the right one.

The copy will be done, if the 'Copy' gadget has been selected (huh? really?!)

If 'incl. Request' has been checked, the request will copied, too.

Leave the window via 'Copy and quit' or 'Cancel' (or press esc).

@ENDNODE


@NODE LaunchShell "Launch shell"

You can start a shell on the MMEditor's screen.

The exact command executed after this menu item has been selected
can be changed via the @{"tooltype SHELLSTART" link EdToolTypes}.

Preset is:

   NewShell "CON:0/0/400/200/CLOSE/MMShell/SCREENMMEditor

@ENDNODE


@NODE LaunchEditor "Launch editor"

You can start an ASCII editor from MMEditor.

The exact command executed after this menu item has been selected
can be changed via the @{"tooltype EDSTART" link EdToolTypes}.

Preset is:

   C:Ed FROM:CON:0/0/400/200/AUTO/CLOSE/Editor/SCREENMMEditor

IF C:Ed is the original Commodore Ed, it will be started on
the screen of MMEditor.

@ENDNODE


@NODE LaunchPaint "Launch a paint programm"

Finally, you can start a paint program - but remember that
a great amount of free (chip!) memory will be very useful
for this purpose!

Preset is:

    DPaint:DPaint

Change the command string by editing the @{"PAINTSTART tooltype" link EdToolTypes}.

@ENDNODE

@REMARK ----------------------------------------------------------------

@NODE Requests "Requests"

Before a command is executed, M&M can ask the user
to give a parameter. This is done via requesters. The result will
be stored in an AmigaDos environment variable, thus it is easy to
use the user's parameter  within (mainly AmigaDos-) commands.

You can either use the AmigaDos command 'GetEnv' (within scripts) or
the '$' character placed before the name of the environment variable.
Please confer the chapter about environment variables (GetEnv/SetEnv)
in your AmigaDos manual to get used to this stuff!

A M&M request uses the following elements:

   - the requester type (1)

   - the requester text (2)

   - the name of the @{"environment variable" link ReqEnvs} (3)
     to which the request's result shall be stored


The following requester types can be used:

   - filename
   - directory
   - textline

   - yes or no		(command will only be executed only
   - okay or cancel	when user selects yes/okay)

   - information	(displaying the requester text only)


				Overview:

--------------------------------------------------------------------------
Req.Type     | It appears        | Requester Text is | In the EnvVar     |
(1)	     |			 | is (2)	     | will be stored (3)|	  |
=========================================================================|
FILENAME     | file requester	 | requester's       | complete filename |
	     |			 | title	     |		  	 |
-------------|-------------------+-------------------+-------------------|
DIRECTORY    | file requester    | requester's	     | directory name  	 |
	     | (directories only)| title	     | plus "/"	 	 |
-------------|-------------------+-------------------+-------------------|
TEXTLINE     | requester with	 | above the textline| text typed by the |
	     | textline          |		     | user		 |
-------------|-------------------+-------------------+-------------------|
YES/NO	     | standard system	 | requester's text  | nothing.		 |
	     | requester	 |		     | comm. only if yes |
-------------|-------------------+-------------------+-------------------|
OKAY/CANCEL  | standard system	 | requester's text  | nothing.		 |
	     | requester	 |		     | comm. only if okay|
-------------|-------------------+-------------------+-------------------|
INFORMATION  | standard system	 | requester's text  | nothing		 |
	     | requester	 |		     |			 |
--------------------------------------------------------------------------


Notice: Whether your menu requests a FILENAME or a DIRECTORY,
        the selected filename  will ALWAYS be stored to the env.var 'MMFile' and
        the selected directory will ALWAYS be stored to the env.var 'MMPath'
        for an easy use within scripts. Use it within scripts!

@ENDNODE

@REMARK ----------------------------------------------------------------

@NODE ReqText "Requester's text"

The requester's text will appear as the title of the file requester,
above the textline to be edited or just within the standard system
requester (Yes/No, Okay/Cancel and Information).

The text within satndard requesters can be wrapped by using the
key combination

   LEFT AMIGA + CONTROL + j

while editing the requester's text. A linefeed character (LF) will be
inserted appearing as a [] character (but smaller!).
Please confer the example menus.

@ENDNODE

@REMARK ----------------------------------------------------------------

@NODE ReqEnvs "Environment variables"

AmigaDos handles so called environment variables. The contents of
those variables are stored to the logical ENV: device. It's easy
to get the information stored within them.

First, you can use the AmigaDos commands

   - 'GetEnv' to read the env.var.
   - 'SetEnv' to write into the env.var.

Second, you can access the information stored within the env.var
by using the string

   - "$nameofenvironmentvariable"

The text 'nameofenvironmentvariable' will automatically replaced
by the content of the env.var!

Example:

	Request: FILENAME	save to: myFile

		 Please select filename!

	Command: EXECUTE DOS COMMAND

		 type "$myFile" to prt:

@ENDNODE

@REMARK ----------------------------------------------------------------

@NODE Commands "Commands"

M&M can handle the following commands:

   @{"execute an AmigaDos command" link CommDos}
   @{"send an ARexx command" link CommRxx}
   @{"display a textfile" link CommTxt}
   @{"switch to another screen" link CommScr}
   @{"quit the menu" link CommStp}
   or no command.


 'Return': Shall M&M return to the menu's execution after the
           command has been runned?

'Options': To set more options concerning the selected command

 'Select': To select the command's argument, for example the
           AmigaDos/ARexx command itself or the name of the
           the screen M&M should jump to.

@ENDNODE

@REMARK ----------------------------------------------------------------

@NODE CommDos "Execute a AmigaDOS command"

Use this command to run any Amiga program.
As you see, this command is the real KERNEL of M&M!

After clicking 'Select', you can influence the following options

  - the output window's @{"x- and y-position, width and height" link GetWin}.

  - the output window's title

  - Screen	  : output window will appear on the MMPlayer's screen,
  		    if not checked: on workbench.

  - Auto	  : output window will only appear, if there is really
  		    some text to put out.

  - Wait	  : output window will be opened until the user clicks
  		    the close gadget or presses ctrl+\.

  - A-Syncron	  : the AmigaDos will be executed a-synron to the other
  	 	    program, so the use is able to select the next menu
  	 	    item, while this AmigaDos command is still running.

  - Stack:	  : Some programs need more than the obligatory 4096
  		    bytes of stack space. Check the program's icon
  		    via workbench command 'Icons/Information' to find
  		    out the needed amount of memory (or confer the
  		    manual of your program).

  - close gadget,
    not draggable,
    not sizeable,
    no border,
    background    : concerning the look of the output window.

@ENDNODE

@REMARK ----------------------------------------------------------------

@NODE CommRxx "Send an ARexx command"

To send any ARexx command or to execute ARexx scripts.

'Port' sets the ARexx port to which your ARexx command or script
shall be sent. Please notice that the port displayed within the
list need not to be ARexx ports!

If you want to execute an ARexx script, you have select "REXX"
as the port (stands for the 'RexxMast' programm, which should
be active while running the menu).

If you want to execute just one ARexx command line, you have to
set the 'command line' option.

Remember that the MMPlayer has an @{"ARexx port called 'MMPlayer'" link PlayerRexx},
which will be active while testrunning from MMEditor, too.

@ENDNODE

@REMARK ----------------------------------------------------------------

@NODE CommTxt "Show a textfile (command)"

Shows an ASCII textfile.

After clicking 'Select', you can influence the following options

  - the textwindow's @{"x- and y-position, width and height" link GetWin}.

  - the font used in the textview window

  - whether the textwindow shall appear on the menu's screen or
    on the workbench

You can also easily select the textfile from the editing window.

The text display depends upon the program @{"'MMTextview'" link TextView} which is
currently not implemented as a stand-alone program (but will be
in future). Looking at the key functions, it is similar to the original
Commodore 'More' program. And it is a very old program which will be
re-programmed in the future.

@ENDNODE

@REMARK ----------------------------------------------------------------

@NODE TextView "Textviewing with M&M"

After loading the ASCII file, there are the following options of
cursing through the text:

  SPACE (or LMB)	next page
  ENTER			next line
  <			first page
  > 			last page
  BACKSPACE		previous page
  q or CTRL+C		Quit textview
  h			Help (back to textview by SPACE)
  F1			show until 10% of text
  F2			show until 20% of text
  (...)
  F0			show until end of text

Jump to the next page by pressing the left mouse button.

@ENDNODE

@REMARK ----------------------------------------------------------------

@NODE CommScr "Switch to other screen (command)"

Choose the screen you want to switch to by clicking 'Select'.
The list of all screens used within the current menu will appear.

If you just want to show another screen which is not used as a
menu screen, select 'other screens'. This will bring a file-requester
on the screen, where you can choose a IFF file. The display of such
a picture can be stopped by pressing the left mouse button or the space
bar. The screen will be closed and the menu's screen will be brought
to front again.

Please notice that the menu's screen will NOT be
closed while showing a picture, thus you will need enough space
for holding many screens (picture, menu's screen, maybe workbench...)
at one time memory.

@ENDNODE

@REMARK ----------------------------------------------------------------

@NODE CommStp "Quit the menu (command)"

Quits the menu. Uh? Really? - Yes!

You can 'Select' a AmigaDos return value. There are presets like
OKAY, WARN, ERROR and FAIL (cnf. your favourite AmigaDos manual).

Notice: The menu will NOT be quitted, if 'Return' has been selected!

@ENDNODE

@REMARK ----------------------------------------------------------------

@NODE GetWin "Set the output window"

The values within the 'X', 'Y', 'Width' and 'Height' gadgets
are giving the window's position and measure.

Click 'Show' to bring the window on screen. Now you can change
position and measure directly. The window is closed after 'Close'
has been clicked.

@ENDNODE


@REMARK *****************************************
@REMARK *					*
@REMARK * Description of the M&M Player program	*
@REMARK *					*
@REMARK *****************************************


@NODE MMPlayer "MMPlayer - the Menus & More Player"

The program MMPlayer is able to play menus created with the
Menus & More Editor MMEditor.

For this purpose MMPlayer opens a @{"public screen" link PlayerScr} and an @{"ARexx port" link PlayerRexx},
with the name 'MMPlayer' (or MMPlayer_1 if started twice, and so on)


Start from Workbench:


  - by double-clicking the MMPlayer icon. A file-requester appears.
    Now you can select a menu project to load.

  - by clicking on a menu project icon, holding the shift-key
    and double clicking the MMPlayer icon. The given menu project
    will be opened automatically.

  - by typing 'MMPlayer' as the default tool within the workbench
    Icon/Information window.

  Note: you can edit the @{"MMPlayer's tooltypes" link PlayerToolTypes} when
        working with the Workbench.


Start from CLI:

  - by typing	1> MMPlayer [projectname]


The running of a menu can be interrupted by pressing Ctrl+Esc (this
behaviour can be switched off by the @{"tooltype BREAK" link PlayerToolTypes}).

If there is still an open window on the menu's screen or another task
uses the screen and MMPlayer tries to close the screen, a message will
appear. Then the user of the menu has to close the window or stop the
task.

@ENDNODE

@REMARK ----------------------------------------------------------------

@NODE PlayerToolTypes "ToolTypes of MMPlayer"

You can change the following tooltypes within the icon's "Information"-
requester:

  WINDOW=doswin

    "doswin" has to be a legal desciption of an AmigaDos window.
    The outputs of the @{"start commands" link StartComm} will be printed into this
    window.

    Preset: CON:0/0/400/200/M&M/AUTO/CLOSE/WAIT


  ERRORREPORT=ON/OFF

    If an error occurs while runnung a menu, a complete error message
    will appear - if this tooltype is set to ON.

    Preset: ON


  BREAK=ON/OFF

    Normally you can interrupt the execution of a menu by
    pressing Ctrl+Esc. If you don't want the user to do so,
    switch this behaviour off with BREAK=OFF.

    Preset: ON

@ENDNODE

@REMARK ----------------------------------------------------------------

@NODE PlayerRexx "MMPlayer's ARexx port"

MMPlayer will open an ARexx port automatically after start.
It has the name 'MMPlayer' (MMPlayer_1 for a second started
MMPlayer and so on).

Unfortunately, the ARexx port currently understands just ONE command :-)

	QUIT	Quits the execution of the menu

But hopefully there will be more commands in one of the next
versions - THIS IS DEPENDS ON YOU, MAN: PAY YOUR SHAREWARE FEE...

@ENDNODE

@NODE PlayerScr "MMPlayer's screen"

MMPlayer opens a public screen for displaying the iff picture.
Thus you can use the screen from third party developments. For example,
you can start the workbench program 'Clock' on the MMPlayer's screen
via the SCREEN option when starting from CLI.

The public screen's name is 'MMPlayer' (MMPlayer_1 if loaded twice)


Example: How to open the shell on the MMPlayer screen

	  1> NewShell CON:0/0/400/100/MyShell/SCREENMMPlayer


Please confer you manual to get more information about public screens.

@ENDNODE


@REMARK *****************
@REMARK *		*
@REMARK *   MMReq Tool	*
@REMARK *		*
@REMARK *****************

@NODE MMReq "MMReq - Menus & More Requester Tool"

MMReq is a short tool program to display a requester on the player
screen. It can easily implemented within AmigaDos scripts.

Unfortunately, it has not been completed yet! :-(
At time, you can only use Okay/Cancell or Yes/No requesters.

You can call it in the following way:

  MMReq [reqText] [reqType]

  reqType can be "OKCANC" or "YESNO"

If the player's screen is open, a requester will be displayed upon it.
If the user selects the negative answer ("cancel" or "no"), an AmigaDos
return code 10 (=FAIL) will be returned.
If the player is not active, an error message appears.


Example: How to call MMReq within an AmigaDos script

	Failat 20
	MMReq YESNO "Copy textfiles to ram disk?"
	IF NOT ERROR
	  Copy #?.txt to RAM:
	ENDIF
	MMReq YESNO "Keep old files?"
	IF ERROR
	  Delete #?.txt
	ENDIF


Another example is in the "Install.bat" file, which is called
by the M&M project "First!.M&M"

@ENDNODE


@REMARK *************************
@REMARK *			*
@REMARK *    MMAnalyse Tool	*
@REMARK *			*
@REMARK *************************


@NODE MMAnalyse "MMAnalyse - The Menus & More Analyse Tool"

Basically, the only task of MMAnalyse is to print out the filenames
of all IFF screens used by a M&M menu project.

MMEditor stores those filenames to the project file. When running
the menu, it could happen that the Player cannot find a screen file.
With MMAnalyse you are able to find out which screens the player
tries to load.

Another possible application: If you want to copy a complete menu
project WITH the screen files, you can create a list.

Get more information about every screen (like resolution or startup
commands) by giving the "FULL" option.


Start from workbench:

  - click on the project's icon, press shift and click on the
    MMAnalyse icon or

  - click on the MMAnalyse icon and select a file within the
    file requester

  Note: The "FULL" option is switched on as standard when starting
        from Workbench. It can be discarded by the ToolType

          FULL=OFF


Start from CLI:

  - type

    1> MMAnalyse [project] [FULL/S]

@ENDNODE


@REMARK *************************
@REMARK *			*
@REMARK *    Miscellaneous...	*						*
@REMARK *			*
@REMARK *************************

@NODE Examples "Example menu projects"

Please have a lookk at the example projects - they might contain some
interesting clues for you...


FuncTest.M&M		For testing all possibilites of M&M. The current
			directory will be printed after start, so don't
			worry about the time, the menu needs to start...

BigFuncTest.M&M		like the one above, but opens a huge screen for
			demonstrating the auto-scroll function.
			You will need the ECS chipset.

EnhancedEd.M&M		demonstrates the possibilites of using ARexx.
			You'll need the original Commodore "Ed" program,
			placed in your C: directory.
			Sorry, but the Load button doesn't work...

ZooCom.M&M		A front-end for the zoo packer.

M2Dev.M&M		A front-end for the M2Amiga compiler system.

MakeV3.1.M&M		My own menu for the generating of M&M. It calls
			scripts which are not implemented in the M&M
			package. It uses the productivity screen-mode.

JukeBox.M&M		demonstrates how to call soundtracker modules
			from a menu. Runs in productivity mode.

@ENDNODE

